#include <windows.h> 
#include <tlhelp32.h> 
#include<iostream> 
 ever caught yourself desperately wanting  
   to know what  
  process has a certain window open, or what window belongs to a 
 certain process? 
 Well, here's a quick and easy way  
    to find out We're going to be using 
     a little  
     bit of Win32 API
Further Reading: child windows 
  
  All applications have at least  
    one window,  
  most have several Normal windows   
   can be enumerated 
 with the EnumWindows function,   
 which we will look at shortly First 

  let's see how to enumerate   
  all the top-level windows   
  in the current desktop 
The EnumWindows function  
  takes a callback function   
 as a parameter The callback 
function will be called once   
  for each top-level window in the 
 current desktop The callback 
  function has the following 
   prototype: 
 BOOL CALLBACK EnumWindowsProc(  
    HWND hwnd,      // handle to parent window 
    LPARAM lParam   // application-defined value 
   ); 
 The EnumWindowsProc function 
 must return a nonzero value   
  to continue enumeration If the 
  function returns zero, 
   enumeration stops The 
function's parameters are as follows: 
• hwnd: Handle to the top-level 
 window The handle is valid only   
 during the enumeration, 
 so don't save this handle 
  HWND_TOPMOST: Begins the enumeration from the top. 
 skip all hanging or owned windows 
 Set last parameter to enumerate 
   only visible windows 
clsName and titleName safely above MAX_PATH 

   EnumWindows(EnumWindowsProc, topmostFlag); 
 topmostFlag can be one of the following: 

 All top-level windows on the 
current desktop are displayed  
 starting at the bottom  
 of the Z-order Last parameter 
set to 0 will enumerate owned   
and hanging windows as well 
 All top-level windows are inner 
 window Klass of this window 

      Set last parameter to 1 to  
           enumerate only visible participator
